##Chinese students return to China after 17-hour stopover: report in depth

Wechat Bqshenyidu

Features, Beijing Youth Daily, the official public number

Reporter / Guo Huimin

Editor / Yang Baolu & Song Jianhua

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Late at night, supplies await clearance outside the Boryspil International Airport

After returning home with 83 boxes of donated "Human Flesh" , Zhang found that he was temporarily unable to return to Ukraine to continue his studies.

The moment she received the letter of thanks from the People's Hospital in Ya'an's Yucheng district, Xu broke down in tears. Although the masks she bought were disposable and could not be used in the fever clinic, she was told they would be used in other clinical departments.

As of 8:00 on February 11, there were 42,407 confirmed cases and 23,589 suspected cases of NCP in China. Since January 24,87.764 million donated items worth 286 million yuan have been imported, including 71.799 million masks, 1.533 million protective clothing and 337,000 pairs of goggles, according to the General Administration of Customs.

After 105 busy hours, on February 1 and 2, two batches of donated goods from Chinese Ukrainians landed in Beijing and Sanya, and were sent to receiving units one after another. The materials were bought, packed and shipped by local Chinese relays, and eventually brought back to China by two students from Ukraine.

There was a problem with the customs

At 2:30 a.m. Ukrainian time on February 1, Yao and 37 other people had just unloaded 135 boxes of donated goods from a truck outside the Boryspil International Airport terminal in Kiev when several customs officers in plain clothes stopped them, eight minutes later, uniformed customs officers came to question them, saying their cargo was stacked up in the aisles and blocking traffic.

Yao Yangchunqiu, a Chinese student studying in Ukraine, signed up as a volunteer courier after learning that "flying in the sky, flying in the sky and flying in the sky" (hereinafter referred to as "flying in the sky") was a voluntary carrier of donated materials sent to China by Ukrainian Chinese and overseas Chinese. Among the 37 people called in to help carry the goods were his classmates, local Chinese farmers, workers and private entrepreneurs who donated supplies.

This is the "sky flying" to carry the second batch of goods, including masks, protective clothing, goggles and so on. An hour later, the supplies were moved to the terminal, but there was a problem with customs clearance.

Yang recalled that most of the materials were purchased in batches at prices as if the mask was 50 cents, but the market price was already 4 yuan. In the case of random inspection of goods by Ukrainian customs, the standard for accounting the value of goods declared was the market price, so he was told that the individual carrying the goods could only carry 18 boxes of goods.

The only person on the plane was Yao Yang Chunqiu. Although he had the documents of the domestic material receiving unit with him, he could not convince the customs that these were donated materials. Yao Yangchunqiu surmised that another reason for the customs block was the existence of reselling activities.

"Mr. Huang, the person in charge of the event, was explaining to the customs that this was disaster relief supplies for China and was a free donation from everyone until 5:30, when the customs reluctantly agreed to let me carry 36 boxes of goods, half an hour before the departure time, " Mr. Yao said, after the consultation, he was taken aboard by a flight attendant. "I was very upset, " he said. "I felt it was pointless to do so little because I couldn't save many people. "

Ten minutes later, it was Away from Her. "Sir, you may have to wait another two hours before you can fly, " the stewardess said to Yao. At this point, the volunteers' wechat group also popped up a message: "Hey, little fatty, you can take all this stuff back today! "

It turned out that in order to get all the materials on the plane, Mr. Huang contacted a friend of the Chinese Embassy in Ukraine and asked him to prove that all 135 boxes of materials were donated and had no commercial use, and made an exception for the flight to be delayed from 6:00 to 8:40, allowing time for loading. It was probably the happiest flight delay of his life, Yao recalled. Eventually, due to the limited space on the plane, he took 70 cases with him.

"flying all over the sky" director Liang Lulu, said the materials landed in Sanya on China Standard Time 2, mainly sent to Wenzhou, Ruian, Zhejiang Province, by the Zhejiang Red Cross as the general receiving unit.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The volunteers are repacking their donations

Temporary increase in express flights

Liang Lulu told reporters in Shenzhen once that it took five days from the collection of materials to the arrival of the second batch.

Sky Express is a Chinese logistics and Transportation Company in Ukraine, founded by Liang Lulu and Yu fan in 2017, and currently has 7 employees. Ukraine's high cost of International Express, more restrictions, "flying" cheap prices, and can carry Taobao Express, it is popular with local Chinese.

Liang Lulu and her husband, Yu Fan, returned to Beijing for the Lunar New Year on Jan. 24, but they were greeted by news of the growing severity of the domestic epidemic, as more and more Chinese in Ukraine, groups and businesses asked if there were still flights to China, can carry masks, goggles and other urgently needed domestic protective materials.

Xu has lived in Ukraine since 2011, when she went to study there, where she often shopped on Taobao and got to know each other well. As soon as the pneumonia epidemic hit Weibo, she asked her domestic partners in the shopping group if they needed masks. At the same time, she contacted Liang Lulu to ask about flights, "She said no, I can only comfort you not to worry, as soon as there is a flight, immediately bought and sent. "

"We just felt that we should do something. We only have the resources of logistics and transportation. Let's do it. LET'S REFUEL OUR COMPATRIOTS! " Liang said afterward.

At 6:30 p.m. on January 28, Liang Lulu and his wife decided to carry the anti-epidemic materials donated by Chinese Ukrainians, "hello to all my compatriots in Ukraine, " Liang wrote in a statement. "In this special year of 2020, Ukraine Express has decided to add a temporary flight on the 30th to transport medical supplies. If you need to donate, you can contact us. "

On the same day, staff at the Ya'an People's Hospital in Sichuan found Xu through wechat group and told her that the hospital was seriously short of protective materials and was now accepting donations or purchases. They asked Xu if she could help them buy and provide invoices? "Yes, but I don't want money, " Xu replied

Later that afternoon, Xu began to search for mask manufacturers on the Internet. At the same time, she called one by one and asked, "at that time, masks were hard to buy. Only one still had them in stock. "

Xu Yina's husband drove for two hours, went to the factory to retrieve the mask, and got the factory mask certificate, sent to the warehouse. Eventually, Ms. Xu bought 3,000 disposable face masks, which cost $234, plus shipping. "I wish I had more. It's a drop in the bucket for a hospital. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhang Jingwei returned home with the first batch of materials

105 hours of multi-person relay

Liang Lulu recalled that after the news of compulsory transportation was sent out, everyone responded in succession, with the fastest speed overnight to buy materials to the warehouse. On January 29, Liang Lulu arranged for staff to receive goods at the warehouse without interruption.

Although the packing specifications were explained in advance, there were still a lot of materials that needed to be repacked. The task of repacking was placed on the receiver of the warehouse. Masks and protective clothing needed to be recompressed, and small boxes of materials needed to be repacked.

During the Spring Festival holiday, the company left only one Ukrainian employee on duty. Liang Lulu had to urgently recruit local Chinese and friends to help. As soon as the news was released, more than a dozen people rushed over on the same day, "I had the money and the strength to do it, and if I didn't have the time to buy, I would ship the goods or pack them up, " Yu recalls. "It was just a feeling of being united. "

"When I received the notice on the same day, I sent two vans and two farm workers to go there and finish the delivery, " said Jiang Jinkai, the owner of a Chinese farm, packing, loading and unloading trucks. They worked from 2 p.m. to 10 p.m, the owner of the local restaurant also brought supper to the workers.

On the afternoon of February 1, Jiang Jinkai received a telephone call from Mr. Huang in charge. The warehouse in the urban area was full, and he needed to find another warehouse temporarily to receive goods. He contacted a well connected local village chief to see if he could rent a warehouse in the village, and the chief replied flatly: Yes, and for free.

In addition to packing and shipping, the mission lacks a linchpin -- the carrier -- to bring all its goods, "human flesh, " back to China. Liang Lulu found a friend, Zhang Jingwei, who was studying in Ukraine.

"I said no problem. " Given the severity of the epidemic and the likelihood that he would not be able to return to Ukraine and delay his studies, Zhang said he struggled at first, but eventually agreed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Yu Fan consulted customs officers in Beijing Capital International Airport

17 hours in Almaty

On January 29, in order to let the donated goods pass through customs smoothly, Liang Lulu and Yu fan came to Beijing Capital International Airport, Beijing, to inquire about related matters. Customs staff told them that according to the latest document issued on the 25th, as long as there is a letter of acceptance from a domestic receiving unit at or above the municipal level, donated materials can be taken through the green channel without having to declare, and materials can be taken away by submitting documents that meet the requirements on the spot, the customs will then contact the person in charge on the documents to assist in supplementing the customs declaration procedures, as well as to determine the distribution and use of materials.

At the same time, Liang Lulu went to a friend at the Ukrainian customs office and asked for help with supplies when Ukraine left the country. At 6 pm on January 30(Ukraine time) , Zhang Jingwei and others arrived at Boris Pohl airport in Kiev, Ukraine, with 83 boxes of supplies.

With the help of friends and airline co-ordination, more than half of the seats on the plane were given over to donations. "But when the second batch of goods went through customs, we couldn't brush our faces again to find acquaintances, " Liang said. By contrast, the first shipment went relatively smoothly, except that the carrier had trouble making connections.

About 5 am on the 31st, Zhang Jingxian arrived at the Almaty International Airport connecting flight. An hour later, the customs came to ask: "Are you surnamed Zhang? Have you checked in more than 80 boxes of face masks? " After receiving a positive answer, customs officers took Zhang to his office, confiscated his phone, passport and plane ticket, and for the next nine hours, the two sides engaged in constant communication about where the supplies came from, where they were going, and why they were being used.

"They used the translation software on my phone to ask me where it came from. I said it was emergency supplies donated by Chinese Ukrainians to China. I also took out the documents I had with me, including the letter of acceptance from the receiving unit at home, but they just said it was an international issue and couldn't let me go. "

In desperation, Zhang Jingwei had to say to the other side, "If you want to send me back to Ukraine, you can send me back. If you want to withhold these materials for China, you can withhold them. At that time, Chinese personnel will come to you and ask for them. " After saying these words, zhang Jingwei feel the other side's attitude has changed, let him put out the document all read again, and then signal that he can leave.

China Standard Time arrived in Beijing Capital International Airport at 5 am on February 1 with 1160 kg of donated goods worth RMB140,000. Liang Lulu and his wife rushed to meet the plane, also called a friend to help move. The four men carried 83 boxes out of the Customs House. After the personnel of the relevant receiving units in Harbin removed 50 of the boxes, they continued to deliver the remaining materials to the SF express delivery point in the urban area, where they were mailed in batches.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hsu received a letter of thanks from the hospital

I cried. I was sick from the outbreak

China Standard Time's flight landed in Sanya at 3:44 a.m. on Feb. 2, bringing the two shipments to an end. After rough accounting, including packaging materials required, staff overtime fees, including air tickets with cargo, a total of more than 60,000 yuan in shipping costs.

So far, there have been no new cases of pneumonia in Ukraine, but the impact of the outbreak has been felt by Chinese in Ukraine. Liang said that many Chinese restaurants in the area had seen a marked decline in traffic, with Chinese people taking taxis on the streets and sometimes being turned away. "Some drivers leave their windows open even when they let them on, " he said. When locals see Chinese people on the elevators, they also stay away.

After a few days'rest, Yao returned to Ukraine to continue his studies. By the time he returned, almost all flights to Ukraine had been canceled. He could only fly to Hong Kong and then transfer from Thailand to Ukraine, in Hong Kong, he was almost refused entry, explaining that it was only after a short transit that he was able to get through. "My father gave me 50,000 yuan at that time, and said it was okay to transfer seven or eight times. "

On the return flight, Yao was the only Chinese passenger on board, and the flight attendants had moved all the passengers in front of him and behind him to other seats. Yao felt isolated. "But I understand. "

Zhang's school will start soon, too, as there is no suitable flight back to Ukraine, nor to his hometown of Daqing, Heilongjiang, where he is staying. Promised to do cargo people, Zhang Jingwei had expected such a result, but he decided to return to send such a trip, "after all, the domestic urgent need for these things. "

On February 4, the Ya'an People's Hospital in Sichuan received a mask from Xu Yina and sent her a letter of thanks, "thank you for donating 3,000 surgical masks to the People's Hospital of Yucheng district in Ya'an during this time of crisis for the screening and treatment of the new Crown Disease... on the occasion of the Chinese New Year, I wish you and your family good health and all the best, " the letter read

As soon as she received the news, Xu began to cry. "I myself am a tearful person, weighed down by the epidemic. ". The masks she bought were ordinary disposable masks and could not be used in fever clinics. The People's Hospital of Ya'an told her that the masks would be used in other clinical departments.
